WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:05.360
Hi everybody, my name is Ryan Johnson and I'm a Data Science Advisor here at Posit

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:09.600
and I'm really excited to be back for another Positeam workflow demo

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:13.760
where I'll be discussing Positron, Posit's newest IDE.

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:18.639
Now in a second we're going to jump into a few slides and talk about Positron

00:00:18.639 --> 00:00:22.959
but then we're going to spend the remainder of today inside of Positron

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:25.920
doing some data science that's powered by AI.

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:29.920
So without further ado let's go ahead and jump into it and get started.

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:37.040
All right so let's first talk about what is Positron.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:44.240
For this demo we're going to define Positron as an AI-ready multilingual IDE for data scientists

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.080
but of course it can do a whole lot more.

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:51.840
Now if you've never heard of Positron before maybe you've heard of rstudio.

00:00:51.919 --> 00:00:57.520
rstudio is an IDE that we developed at Posit probably 15 years ago at this point.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:04.559
It's extremely stable, it's beloved by our users and it really is optimized for data science

00:01:04.559 --> 00:01:09.279
because as you're working with data you're creating variables which you can actually

00:01:09.279 --> 00:01:13.760
interact with in the variables pane and maybe you're creating plots or tables

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:18.160
which you can also interact with and see directly inside of the IDE itself.

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:23.680
Now there's also another popular IDE it's called VS Code and while you can't do data

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:29.440
science in VS Code this tends to be an IDE that's extremely popular amongst software developers

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.760
because it is multilingual so you can use R, Python, Julia, HTML, JavaScript.

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:41.120
It's extremely customizable and in newer versions of VS Code it actually comes

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:43.440
AI-equipped with things like GitHub Copilot.

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:48.720
So when designing Positron we really wanted to take the best of both worlds.

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:53.199
So we wanted to take the features that make rstudio optimize for data science and bring

00:01:53.199 --> 00:01:58.320
that into Positron and then also bring in some of the cool features of VS Code

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:01.279
to create this perfect data science focused IDE.

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:07.279
Now again if you've never seen Positron before this is what it looks like in all of its glory.

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:11.119
And you'll first notice that there's a lot of windows and buttons to click

00:02:11.199 --> 00:02:14.639
but we can actually just break down Positron into four components.

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:18.880
Over here on the left hand side we're going to call this like your

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:23.600
manage area where you can manage things like what files are in your project.

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:28.559
You can manage things like version control, your extensions which we'll talk about in a little bit.

00:02:28.559 --> 00:02:30.720
That's all done over here on the left hand side.

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:38.399
Now as you begin writing code whether it be an R script, a Python script, a Shiny application,

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:43.759
a core code document, that's all going to be done right here in the top middle of your screen.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:47.360
And typically when you open up Positron for the first time you'll see this

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:49.600
welcome page with some helpful links and buttons.

00:02:50.479 --> 00:02:56.240
Now as you go to run code whether it be R or Python code because Positron supports both,

00:02:56.240 --> 00:03:00.720
that's done down here at the very bottom where you get an interactive console.

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:04.240
And again you can switch over to a Python console very easily.

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:09.520
Now as you begin working with data again you're probably going to be creating things like

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:14.479
variables or subsets of your data and they're going to be stored in memory.

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:19.199
So any variables that you're creating you can actually see them over here in the top right hand

00:03:19.199 --> 00:03:23.759
corner and then any plots or tables you're creating it will show up down here.

00:03:23.759 --> 00:03:28.559
There's also a viewer tab up here so if you're running things like a Shiny application or you

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:34.080
render an HTML document, a core code document, that's all going to be done over here on the

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:37.520
right hand side which really helps you understand your data.

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:43.360
So that's kind of the Positron 101, but for today's demo we're going to be focusing on some

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:49.279
of the AI features that we've either built into Positron or as built as an extension of Positron.

00:03:49.839 --> 00:03:53.600
And the first one that we're going to get practice leveraging today

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:56.080
is something called Positron Assistant.

00:03:56.080 --> 00:04:01.839
So Positron Assistant again is an AI client that is directly built into Positron.

00:04:01.839 --> 00:04:06.639
In fact on the left hand side of Positron you'll probably see this little robot face,

00:04:06.639 --> 00:04:09.039
that is how you can access Positron Assistant.

00:04:10.399 --> 00:04:14.880
And Positron Assistant can do a lot of great things and you can also interact with it in a

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:15.839
lot of different ways.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:22.000
So when you click this little robot face it'll open this sidebar and you'll get a text box down

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:27.440
There is another way where you can interact with Positron Assistant known as inline edits and

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:29.119
we'll talk about that here in a second.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.679
But something that's really important about Positron Assistant as well as a lot of the

00:04:33.679 --> 00:04:40.799
other AI tools that we're building for Positron is that this tool is model agnostic and it follows

00:04:40.799 --> 00:04:44.559
our bring your own LLM or bring your own model philosophy.

00:04:45.359 --> 00:04:50.720
Now currently we don't have a model for Positron, but we do have a model for Positron that we

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:56.160
Now currently with Positron Assistant as of today it's still in preview support.

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:02.000
We do only support Anthropic but we are actively testing out other models with the hopes that

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:09.279
whatever model your company or group is approved to use that you can bring that model to the table.

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:11.279
And so what does that look like?

00:05:12.399 --> 00:05:17.839
So here's a window that you can open up in Positron where you can select your various model.

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:21.040
Again, currently we only support Anthropic,

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:25.679
but here you can see some other models that we're testing out including AWS Bedrock,

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:30.239
Gemini, GitHub Copilot is supported currently for code completion,

00:05:30.239 --> 00:05:35.600
but we will hopefully support it as a full-fledged LLM in the near future and others as well.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:39.600
And setting up these models is super simple.

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:42.640
Like, for example, with Anthropic, you can just apply an API key.

00:05:43.519 --> 00:05:45.440
It tends to work pretty seamlessly.

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:50.079
Now the other important thing to note about Positron Assistant is that it is designed

00:05:50.079 --> 00:05:51.679
for data science.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:57.760
And when I say that, I mean that it's designed to have context awareness.

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:01.679
So when you start interacting with it, it knows about your data science environment.

00:06:01.679 --> 00:06:02.799
So what do I mean by that?

00:06:04.399 --> 00:06:08.480
So here I have another picture of Positron and here's Positron Assistant over here on

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:14.000
the left-hand side and I purposely gave it these really creepy eyeballs because

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.239
as you interact with Positron Assistant and you ask it questions down here,

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:21.040
it can actually see your environment.

00:06:21.679 --> 00:06:24.559
Things like what scripts do you have open?

00:06:24.559 --> 00:06:26.799
What variables do you have stored in memory?

00:06:26.799 --> 00:06:29.200
What plots or tables have you created?

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:32.239
What code have you run and what output from that code was run?

00:06:32.239 --> 00:06:33.519
It can see that.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:39.920
That way, when you ask it questions, typically the suggestions that Positron Assistant just

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:41.519
tend to work immediately.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:46.480
Another way to think about this is if maybe you're using like ChatGPT or Gemini to help

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:49.760
with some code assistance, you're using like the web interface.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:55.279
If you have a code question, typically you have to copy and paste all of your code, copy

00:06:55.279 --> 00:07:00.559
and paste the error message, potentially copy and paste a subset of your data in order to

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:05.600
give that model enough context to provide hopefully a useful suggestion.

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:08.239
But with Positron Assistant, you don't have to do that.

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:11.040
But with Positron Assistant, you don't have to do that.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:15.920
You can give it a simple request and it will understand your context and provide suggestions

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:17.279
that, again, just tend to work.

00:07:19.679 --> 00:07:25.040
Now, that text box down here in the sidebar is one way to leverage Positron Assistant.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:29.519
But there's another one known as inline code suggestions, which we'll do in today's demo

00:07:29.519 --> 00:07:30.399
as well.

00:07:30.399 --> 00:07:33.519
But the idea here is that maybe you have a script open.

00:07:33.519 --> 00:07:36.399
It could be a Quarto document like in this screenshot.

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:39.440
It could be an R script, a Python script, a Shiny app.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.600
And you can place your cursor somewhere in this document and hit Control-I if you're

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:46.320
in a Windows machine or Command-I if you're on a Mac machine.

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:49.440
And it opens up this little text box.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:51.279
And this is Positron Assistant.

00:07:51.279 --> 00:07:56.320
You can ask it questions and it will provide suggestions inline with the rest of your code.

00:07:58.799 --> 00:08:02.959
Now, Positron Assistant is one tool that we're going to focus in on today.

00:08:02.959 --> 00:08:05.839
But the other one is something called DataBot.

00:08:06.559 --> 00:08:09.600
Now, DataBot is actually available as an extension.

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:12.640
So, it's not built into Positron like Positron Assistant.

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:14.160
It's available as an extension.

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:20.000
And in a second, we'll kind of show you where that lives and how you can install extensions

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:21.040
inside of Positron.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:28.239
But to talk a little bit about DataBot, I first want to help clarify, like, when to

00:08:28.239 --> 00:08:31.119
use DataBot and when to use Positron Assistant.

00:08:32.080 --> 00:08:39.200
DataBot is specifically designed to do exploratory data analysis and to do it really fast.

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:41.200
And actually, it's surprisingly a lot of fun.

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:46.960
So, imagine you get some brand new data thrown at you and you want to analyze it.

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:49.280
That is a really good use case for DataBot.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.640
Now, for Positron Assistant, this can certainly do a lot of things that DataBot can do.

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:56.880
But it tends to be more task-focused.

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:01.440
So, maybe you have an error that you need to debug or you have a plot you want to approve

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:04.159
or you want to create, like, an individual table.

00:09:04.159 --> 00:09:07.280
Those are really great tasks for Positron Assistant.

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:13.679
Now, the way that DataBot works to do this exploratory data analysis is it implements

00:09:13.679 --> 00:09:15.840
what we're calling this where loop.

00:09:16.719 --> 00:09:20.159
So, you have some data and you want to learn more about that data.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:23.039
So, you ask DataBot to start analyzing it.

00:09:23.039 --> 00:09:26.719
And what it's going to do is first write some R or Python code.

00:09:26.719 --> 00:09:32.479
It will execute that code immediately, analyze the results, regroup with suggestions,

00:09:32.479 --> 00:09:34.479
and then just wait for your next instructions.

00:09:35.039 --> 00:09:40.000
And this will just go around and around and around in circles until you're happy with

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:43.760
the results and you've gleaned all the information you need from that data.

00:09:45.119 --> 00:09:49.760
Now, it's also important to note that this where loop and also the way that Positron

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:52.719
Assistant works is that it's all code-based.

00:09:53.039 --> 00:09:57.520
All the suggestions you're getting from DataBot are just code suggestions.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:01.919
And we think that code is the most auditable way to explore data with AI.

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:05.840
Because you're not just asking it a question and then sending it off into some black box

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:07.840
and getting a magical response.

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:09.280
You are actually getting code.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:10.239
You can see that code.

00:10:10.239 --> 00:10:13.200
You can approve that code before it actually gets run.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:15.760
All right.

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:18.799
So, with that, we're going to jump into Positron.

00:10:18.799 --> 00:10:21.760
And we're going to demo all these really cool features we just talked about.

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:27.440
So, the first thing we'll do is we're going to give you all just a little Positron 101,

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.440
get you comfortable with the user interface.

00:10:30.719 --> 00:10:34.000
We're then going to step into doing some AI-powered data science.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.559
And we're going to begin with Positron Assistant.

00:10:36.559 --> 00:10:40.159
And we're going to use Positron Assistant to help us debug an error.

00:10:40.799 --> 00:10:44.080
We're then going to improve a GG plot.

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:46.880
And then we'll even create a GT table from scratch.

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:53.280
And then we're going to wrap up today by doing some fast exploratory data analysis with DataBot.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:55.119
All right.

