So, here's a project on GitHub,

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:43.280
a repository that we've created for some workshops.

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:45.520
And I'm going to go ahead and just grab this URL,

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.960
come on back to Positron and paste it in.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:50.880
And then we'll click OK.

00:15:52.239 --> 00:15:57.200
Now, anytime you create a new project inside of Positron,

00:15:57.200 --> 00:15:59.840
it always opens up a new Positron session.

00:15:59.840 --> 00:16:01.520
So, we'll give it a few seconds here to boot up.

00:16:04.159 --> 00:16:05.280
All right, here we go.

00:16:06.719 --> 00:16:08.239
And we'll know we're in the right place

00:16:08.239 --> 00:16:11.280
because we see now over here on the left-hand side,

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:14.479
this icon in the very top left, this like page icon.

00:16:14.479 --> 00:16:17.200
This is your file explorer where you can see

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:21.599
what files or datasets are inside of your current project.

00:16:21.679 --> 00:16:23.440
So, these are all the files that I just pulled

00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:24.799
into my Git repository.

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:27.280
And if we just quickly run through them,

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:29.919
you'll see there's some CSV files

00:16:29.919 --> 00:16:34.080
and they correspond to various years from 2015 to 2019.

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:36.080
We're going to be exploring this data here in a second.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:40.159
You'll also notice that there's some QMD files,

00:16:40.159 --> 00:16:42.320
which again stands for Quarto.

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:44.080
And we'll be talking through some of these as well,

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:46.559
including the Python one and this R one.

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:48.880
There's also a README file down here

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:52.000
and an RNVLOC file, which is associated with the RM package

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:53.200
that we created here at Posit.

00:16:54.479 --> 00:16:56.080
Now, we'll also know we're in the right place

00:16:56.080 --> 00:16:57.359
if you look in the top right corner,

00:16:57.359 --> 00:16:59.520
you'll see the Positron AI Workshop one.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:01.760
That's the directory that I'm currently working within.

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:05.520
All right, so to get started here,

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:08.719
let me just navigate you from the left-hand side,

00:17:08.719 --> 00:17:10.640
this ribbon over here.

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:12.800
I mentioned in the slides, Positron Assistant.

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:15.040
That's the little robot face down here.

00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:16.880
We're in a very short amount of time.

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:19.040
We're going to actually open up Positron Assistant

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:20.400
and play around with it.

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:22.319
But I want to get you kind of familiar

00:17:22.319 --> 00:17:23.839
with the rest of Positron.

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:26.719
So kind of moving through some of these icons,

00:17:26.719 --> 00:17:28.160
you know, we would highly encourage you

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:29.680
to play around with them,

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:31.280
see what these various icons do.

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:32.880
But I just want to point out a few of them.

00:17:33.439 --> 00:17:36.479
The first one here is source control, version control.

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:40.479
Now, I've been an RStudio user for like over a decade

00:17:40.479 --> 00:17:43.040
and the get features inside of RStudio are good.

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:47.040
But I would say that the get features inside of Positron

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:49.040
just take it to a whole new level.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:50.959
All right, you can see here this repository,

00:17:50.959 --> 00:17:53.280
all the various commits that we've added.

00:17:53.839 --> 00:17:56.719
We have the ability to access a lot more get commands

00:17:56.719 --> 00:17:59.359
directly within Positron.

00:17:59.359 --> 00:18:01.839
And if needed to, you always have access to the terminal

00:18:01.839 --> 00:18:03.839
if you need to access get more natively.

00:18:05.680 --> 00:18:08.000
And then the other icon I want to point out for right now

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
is going to be these squares.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:11.680
These are known as your extensions.

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:15.839
Now, for anyone here who has never used VS Code before,

00:18:16.479 --> 00:18:18.640
this may be a bit of a foreign concept,

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:23.760
but extensions are a way for you to install these extensions

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:26.160
that help kind of modify

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:28.479
and fine tune your developer experience.

00:18:29.199 --> 00:18:31.280
Now, by clicking on this extensions icon,

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:32.640
it actually shows you all the ones

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:34.000
that are currently installed,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:35.439
including this, you know,

00:18:35.439 --> 00:18:37.359
our language support formatter called air,

00:18:37.359 --> 00:18:38.400
which is really cool.

00:18:38.959 --> 00:18:40.959
But importantly, the second one down here

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:42.160
is data bot.

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:44.719
So data bot, that extension I talked about

00:18:44.719 --> 00:18:47.520
to do fast exploratory data analysis.

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:48.959
And we're actually going to talk about this one

00:18:48.959 --> 00:18:49.760
here in a little bit.

00:18:50.319 --> 00:18:52.160
And you'll see it as a few other ones as well

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:54.160
that we pre-installed into this demo environment.

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:56.560
But if you wanted to install another one,

00:18:56.560 --> 00:18:59.119
you can search the marketplace up here

00:18:59.119 --> 00:19:00.160
and search for, you know,

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:01.760
whatever extension you want.

00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:04.400
And what's really cool about Positron

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:07.280
is that it's built on the same open source framework

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:08.560
as VS Code.

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:09.599
So for the most part,

00:19:09.599 --> 00:19:11.839
any extension you use in VS Code

00:19:11.839 --> 00:19:13.599
will also work in Positron.

00:19:15.439 --> 00:19:17.359
Now, the only other thing I'll mention for right now

00:19:17.359 --> 00:19:19.439
to get you familiar with Positron

00:19:19.439 --> 00:19:21.839
is this search bar at the very top.

00:19:21.839 --> 00:19:23.280
Again, if you're a VS Code user,

00:19:23.280 --> 00:19:24.400
this should look familiar.

00:19:24.400 --> 00:19:26.000
But if you're an RStudio user,

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.839
this may be a new feature.

00:19:27.839 --> 00:19:29.920
And it's a really important one in Positron

00:19:29.920 --> 00:19:32.239
because it can do a variety of things.

00:19:32.239 --> 00:19:33.760
But what I want to point out for right now

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:35.920
is something known as your command palette.

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:36.719
And there's a few ways

00:19:36.719 --> 00:19:38.160
you can access the command palette.

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:39.920
You could click this search bar

00:19:40.479 --> 00:19:42.400
and select show and run commands.

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:43.599
It essentially just puts a little

00:19:43.599 --> 00:19:44.640
greater than symbol there.

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:45.839
That's one way.

00:19:45.839 --> 00:19:47.680
Or it is a keyboard shortcut.

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:48.800
So I'm on a Mac machine,

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:50.400
it's command shift P.

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:51.839
I think it'd be control shift P

00:19:51.839 --> 00:19:52.880
if you're on a Windows machine.

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:55.839
And then here's all the various commands.

00:19:55.839 --> 00:19:56.800
And you can see some of them

00:19:56.800 --> 00:19:59.280
are associated with extensions like air.

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:01.760
There's so many to choose from.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:04.400
It could certainly be a little bit overwhelming.

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:06.000
But just know that this actually has

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.079
really nice like fuzzy searching.

00:20:08.079 --> 00:20:10.719
So for example, if I wanted to open up a file,

00:20:10.719 --> 00:20:12.479
if I didn't know the actual command,

00:20:12.479 --> 00:20:14.319
I could just say like file open,

00:20:14.319 --> 00:20:14.959
something like that.

00:20:14.959 --> 00:20:16.400
And there you go, open file.

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:19.040
All right.

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:20.719
So in order to get kind of familiar

00:20:20.719 --> 00:20:22.160
with the rest of Positron,

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:24.000
we're actually going to first

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:25.760
open up a core to a document.

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:27.439
Now, before I do that,

00:20:27.439 --> 00:20:29.439
I want you to take your attention up here

00:20:29.439 --> 00:20:30.400
to the top right.

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:33.439
You'll see currently in this Positron session,

00:20:33.439 --> 00:20:36.400
I'm running R version 4.4.0.

00:20:37.280 --> 00:20:39.520
Now I mentioned before that Positron

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:40.479
right out of the box

00:20:40.479 --> 00:20:42.079
is designed to work equally well

00:20:42.079 --> 00:20:43.760
with both R and Python.

00:20:44.479 --> 00:20:46.479
So I could easily click this button,

00:20:47.199 --> 00:20:48.640
select a new interpreter,

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:50.479
and open up a Python session.

00:20:50.479 --> 00:20:51.920
And that would work perfectly fine.

00:20:52.719 --> 00:20:54.640
But what I could also do is

00:20:54.640 --> 00:20:56.319
you'll see there's a core to a document

00:20:56.319 --> 00:20:58.079
called python.qmd.

00:20:58.079 --> 00:20:59.839
So let me go ahead and click on this file.

00:21:00.479 --> 00:21:02.800
Again, it's going to open up here in the top middle.

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:04.079
And you can always click and drag

00:21:04.079 --> 00:21:05.359
the dividers of Positron

00:21:05.359 --> 00:21:06.319
to give you some more space.

00:21:07.439 --> 00:21:09.359
Now, if you're not familiar with quarto,

00:21:09.359 --> 00:21:10.160
in a lot of ways,

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:12.160
they're similar to like R Markdown

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:13.920
and also Jupyter Notebooks.

00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:16.319
It's a way for you to combine both code.

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:19.680
You can see these like gray code cells

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:20.560
with some text here,

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:22.640
which will ultimately get rendered to HTML.

00:21:24.079 --> 00:21:24.319
All right.

00:21:24.319 --> 00:21:26.079
Now, by opening up this Python

00:21:26.079 --> 00:21:27.040
core to a document,

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:28.400
you'll notice something kind of cool.

00:21:29.119 --> 00:21:32.239
That Positron automatically detected

00:21:32.239 --> 00:21:34.000
that this core to a document

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.079
includes Python code.

00:21:36.079 --> 00:21:38.239
So without me doing anything else,

00:21:38.239 --> 00:21:40.640
Positron automatically opened up

00:21:40.640 --> 00:21:42.079
a Python kernel for me.

00:21:42.079 --> 00:21:43.359
So now you can see I currently have

00:21:43.359 --> 00:21:46.560
Python version 3.12.3 running.

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:49.040
And I could even switch back to my R version.

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:51.839
This is an insanely powerful feature of Positron

00:21:51.839 --> 00:21:53.680
where you can have both R and Python

00:21:53.680 --> 00:21:55.199
running at the same time.

00:21:55.199 --> 00:21:58.079
You can even have multiple R versions

00:21:58.079 --> 00:22:00.000
and multiple Python versions

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.839
all running at the exact same time.

00:22:01.839 --> 00:22:03.680
And they all have their unique environment.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:07.280
Now, if I was to run a cell here within Python,

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:09.520
so I can click run cell here above line eight,

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:11.359
and it's going to do some things

00:22:11.359 --> 00:22:12.880
like import some packages,

00:22:13.599 --> 00:22:14.719
but it's also going to create

00:22:14.719 --> 00:22:16.959
a variable called happiness.

00:22:16.959 --> 00:22:18.319
And what this line of Python

00:22:18.319 --> 00:22:20.079
here on line 16 does

00:22:20.079 --> 00:22:22.239
is it reads in a CSV file

00:22:22.239 --> 00:22:23.280
that's in my project.

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:25.199
It's this file over here, 2019.

00:22:26.079 --> 00:22:27.439
And so by doing so,

00:22:27.439 --> 00:22:28.800
you'll notice over here again

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:30.160
in our sessions pane,

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:31.839
we now have some variables created.

00:22:32.560 --> 00:22:34.959
And this is a powerful feature of Positron.

00:22:34.959 --> 00:22:36.880
You can see the variables you've created

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:38.640
and you can actually interact with them.

00:22:39.199 --> 00:22:41.920
So here I've created this happiness data.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:43.839
And if I click on this grid icon,

00:22:43.839 --> 00:22:44.959
it's going to open up

00:22:44.959 --> 00:22:47.359
our interactive data viewer

00:22:47.359 --> 00:22:49.040
inside of Positron.

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:49.920
So let me click on this.

00:22:51.680 --> 00:22:52.479
All right, you'll see that

00:22:52.479 --> 00:22:54.719
it opens up here in the middle,

00:22:54.719 --> 00:22:56.239
but I'm actually going to

00:22:56.239 --> 00:22:57.839
hide some of my windows here

00:22:57.839 --> 00:22:59.359
to give us some more space.

00:22:59.359 --> 00:23:00.719
And I think this is an important thing

00:23:00.719 --> 00:23:01.920
as you get more comfortable

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:05.040
using Positron to be aware of windows,

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:06.880
sidebars, and you can always hide them

00:23:06.880 --> 00:23:07.839
and pop them back in.

00:23:08.479 --> 00:23:09.680
A lot of that you can do up here

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:11.839
in the top right hand corner.

00:23:11.839 --> 00:23:13.920
So right now I don't need my files

00:23:13.920 --> 00:23:15.119
pane over here on the left hand side.

00:23:15.119 --> 00:23:16.000
So I'll hide that.

00:23:17.119 --> 00:23:18.239
I'm going to go ahead and hide

00:23:18.239 --> 00:23:19.760
this sidebar off to the right,

00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:21.520
which I can click this right one here.

00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:23.280
And I'll go ahead and hide my console,

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:24.800
which is the middle button.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:26.880
And now we can see this really cool data

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:28.239
viewer in all of its glory.

00:23:29.119 --> 00:23:30.640
So this is looking at, again,

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:32.800
at this happiness variable data set

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:33.520
that we created.

00:23:34.319 --> 00:23:35.199
And if you see here,

00:23:35.199 --> 00:23:37.040
we get a nice scrollable view.

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:38.400
This is in a lot of ways

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:39.439
similar to the data viewer

00:23:39.439 --> 00:23:40.479
inside of RStudio,

00:23:40.479 --> 00:23:42.160
but it's a little bit more powerful.

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:44.239
And we can also see over here

00:23:44.239 --> 00:23:45.280
on the left hand side,

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:46.479
all the various columns

00:23:46.479 --> 00:23:48.000
and information about

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:48.959
those various columns,

00:23:48.959 --> 00:23:51.839
like if they're numeric or a character,

00:23:51.839 --> 00:23:53.040
and you can click on them

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:55.119
and get some more statistics

00:23:55.119 --> 00:23:56.560
about each individual column.

00:23:57.520 --> 00:23:58.800
Now this data set,

00:23:58.800 --> 00:23:59.599
and I'll just point you

00:23:59.599 --> 00:24:01.199
to two columns here,

00:24:01.199 --> 00:24:02.000
you'll see it's looking

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:03.199
at various countries,

00:24:03.839 --> 00:24:04.959
and then they're being assigned

00:24:04.959 --> 00:24:06.719
like a happiness score,

00:24:06.719 --> 00:24:07.520
like how happy are

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:08.959
these various countries.

00:24:08.959 --> 00:24:09.920
It also includes some other

00:24:09.920 --> 00:24:11.280
information like GDP,

00:24:11.280 --> 00:24:11.920
social support,

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:12.880
and it gives various scores

00:24:12.880 --> 00:24:13.439
there as well.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:16.000
So with this data viewer,

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:17.199
what you can actually do

00:24:17.199 --> 00:24:18.640
is you can interact with a column

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:20.239
by clicking these three dots.

00:24:20.239 --> 00:24:21.760
You can sort them.

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:23.439
You can also add a filter.

00:24:23.439 --> 00:24:24.160
So for example,

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:25.280
if I wanted to filter

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:28.319
all the various rows here

00:24:28.319 --> 00:24:30.000
where the score is,

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.319
let's say greater than seven.

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:35.359
I've now done that.

00:24:36.319 --> 00:24:37.439
And then maybe I also want

00:24:37.439 --> 00:24:39.119
to filter my countries.

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:41.520
Or maybe I'll filter the rank actually.

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:43.280
I'll say add a filter

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:44.160
and I want to extract

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:45.199
just the top 10.

00:24:45.199 --> 00:24:49.599
So I can say is between one and 10.

00:24:49.599 --> 00:24:51.199
And I'll apply that filter.

00:24:51.199 --> 00:24:51.599
There we go.

00:24:51.599 --> 00:24:53.359
There's our top 10 happiest countries

00:24:53.359 --> 00:24:54.239
in 2019.

00:24:55.119 --> 00:24:56.479
Now, a really cool feature

00:24:56.479 --> 00:24:58.000
that's currently available in Python

00:24:58.000 --> 00:24:59.439
and coming very soon to R

00:24:59.439 --> 00:25:00.479
is if you look up here

00:25:00.479 --> 00:25:01.199
at the very top,

00:25:01.199 --> 00:25:02.880
you'll see convert to code.

00:25:03.439 --> 00:25:04.959
So as you do like sorting

00:25:04.959 --> 00:25:05.839
and filtering

00:25:05.839 --> 00:25:06.800
and other transformations

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:07.599
to your data set

00:25:07.599 --> 00:25:08.640
here in the data viewer,

00:25:09.359 --> 00:25:11.119
if you want to make that repeatable

00:25:11.119 --> 00:25:12.239
and reproducible,

00:25:12.239 --> 00:25:14.079
you can simply click this button

00:25:14.079 --> 00:25:15.439
and it will actually spit out,

00:25:15.439 --> 00:25:15.920
in this case,

00:25:15.920 --> 00:25:17.119
some pandas code

00:25:17.119 --> 00:25:18.560
so you can replicate

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:19.680
what you've done to that data.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:20.319
And I think that's

00:25:20.319 --> 00:25:21.760
a really cool feature

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:23.119
that you only find in Positron.

00:25:25.199 --> 00:25:26.640
All right.

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:28.959
So let me go ahead back in here.

00:25:28.959 --> 00:25:31.040
And what we're going to do next

00:25:31.040 --> 00:25:32.079
is I'm going to open up

00:25:32.079 --> 00:25:33.359
